rk of community support that propelled him to college and DREAM Act organizing but still landed in a factory job a few short years after graduation, and the early-exiters, like Gabriel, who failed to make meaningful connections in high school and started navigating dead-end jobs, immigration checkpoints, and a world narrowly circumscribed by legal limitations. This vivid ethnography explores why highly educated undocumented youth share similar work and life outcomes with their less-educated peers, despite the fact that higher education is touted as the path to integration and success in America. Mining the results of an extraordinary twelve-year study that followed 150 undocumented young adults in Los Angeles, Lives in Limbo exposes the failures of a system that integrates children into K-12 schools but ultimately denies them the rewards of their labor.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChildren of illegal aliensxEducationxUnited States. 0aChildren of illegal aliensxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aChildren of illegal alienszUnited StatesxEducation. 0aChildren of illegal alienszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 4aanthropologist. 4abroken immigration system. 4acollege student. 4acollege-goer. 4adaca. 4adream act. 4aeconomist. 4afuture of an undocumented worker. 4ak-12 schools. 4alinguist. 4amanual laborers. 4amexican american immigrants. 4amexican american youth. 4asociologist. 4atwelve-year study. 4auncertain future. 4aundocumented immigrants. 4aunited states immigration policies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertU